<section>
  <h2>Summary</h2>
  <p>
    Lyskova et al. present new spectroscopic redshifts for galaxies in the field of the "Peanut" cluster (SRGe J023820.8+200556; z~0.42) and interpret the system as a candidate massive, nearly head-on cluster merger observed shortly after pericenter — an analogue to rare systems like the Bullet cluster or El Gordo. Using the 6-m BTA telescope the authors add 26 redshifts (31 total secure galaxy redshifts) and analyse the line-of-sight velocity distribution together with X-ray imaging from eROSITA/Chandra.
  </p>

  <h3>Key findings</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>New spectroscopic sample: 26 new redshifts (31 total secure members) around z~0.4095–0.4360.</li>
    <li>Velocity distribution: possible bimodality with components near z~0.425 and z~0.416; brightest galaxies show a line-of-sight velocity separation of order ~2000 km s⁻¹, though statistical tests do not conclusively require two subclusters.</li>
    <li>If treated as a single system: measured line-of-sight velocity dispersion sigma_los = 1455 ± 83 km s⁻¹, implying M200 ≈ 2×10^15 M☉ using standard velocity-dispersion → mass scaling relations.</li>
    <li>X-ray morphology: Chandra/eROSITA images show two bright gas substructures and offsets between galaxies and hot gas, consistent with a major merger near pericenter (spatial offsets analogous to the Bullet cluster).</li>
    <li>Interpretation: the combined optical spectroscopic and X-ray evidence favours a major merger viewed shortly after pericenter, but spectroscopic substructure tests (e.g., Dressler–Schectman) leave some ambiguity about whether two distinct subclusters are statistically required.</li>
  </ul>

