  <h2>Key numbers / claims (for citation)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>New redshifts: 26 (31 total secure member redshifts reported).</li>
    <li>Redshift range covered: z ≈ 0.4095–0.4360.</li>
    <li>Suggested line-of-sight velocity separation between brightest galaxies / candidate subclusters: ≈ 2000 km s⁻¹.</li>
    <li>Measured single-system velocity dispersion: sigma_los = 1455 ± 83 km s⁻¹.</li>
    <li>Implied mass (via sigma → M200 scaling): M200 ≈ 2×10^15 M☉ (order-of-magnitude; depends on scaling choice).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Notes</h2>
  <p>
    The spectroscopic sample remains small (31 galaxies), so kinematic substructure is suggestive but not definitive; the authors caution that formal statistical tests do not conclusively prefer a two-component model. The strength of the paper lies in combining these redshifts with X-ray morphology showing clear gas substructure and offsets, which together make a plausible case for a recent, nearly head-on major merger. This system is relevant for studies of cluster dynamics, extreme-mass cluster abundance, and tests of dark-matter behaviour in high-velocity collisions.
  </p>

